Text: The highlights of this week were definitely the client interview and the Friday workshop.
I personally felt the client clearly knows what they're after and are willing to make compromises along the way.
In fact, I think it was Eric (or Kuku) who proactively narrowed down the scope to just the national data set and a few other important states.
Overall, the goal is very clear as well.
Eric wants to expand his business to include other areas within and outside his current coverage.
Technically speaking, he wants a national database of suppliers that would complement his already functioning trucker database.
The business model is not something too exotic as well, as in my mind it's just a form of Uber-Eat, only that it's dirt rather than donuts.

And this will definitely make it easier to search for relevant solutions, as undoubtedly other companies operating similar brokerage model must have some ways to organize and maintain an active database of vendors and clients.
All in all, the fact that I put this project as my number 2 (second only to Winely) it's a step from the last project where I didn't really pay attention to the clarity of the requirements.
Moreover, I'm excited to learn a lot from Kuku as well, who obviously has a lot to offer given that he's running Logic Studio.
Speaking of someone who knows his trade, Teacher3 has been great and hopefully I and my team can employ some of the techniques throughout our project.
Personally, his insights are very useful to me as it gives me a way to structure, measure, and reflect on what I should and can reasonably achieve within a set of constraints.
This is extremely important as it gives team members a sense of direction and accountability, as well as a easy-going yet productive way of negotiating workloads.
For this week, the goal is obviously the proposal, presentation, and personal learning goals.
As a team, we have started on certain aspects on our own but haven't had a chance to regroup since Friday.
Hopefully those who haven't replied will quickly decide on a time so that we can get a move on.

Still, it appears to me that the project is made up of four smaller separate components:  a static data pipeline based on the text files, a on-demand API pipeline based on USA's govt database, the map interface, and the database (which may turn out to be just a big table).
Since each of them is quite a project in their own, I hope that through meetings and communication with our client we will manage to scope it down.
Further down the road, I'd like to work on other parts than mapping as I've been doing quite a lot of that for a personal project with Toto as part of a visualisation for Stat NZ.
Of course, I'd be more than happy to help a member who would like to take charge of the mapping part if I could be useful.
On a side note, I've been meaning to gather some user feedback by asking people to give the website a try, so I hope you guys wouldn't mind my sharing it here.
It basically visualizes how Kiwis traveled to work and school in 2018.
If you guys can spare some time I'd appreciate any feedback on pretty much anything.
It's hosted on Git at:  https: //thangpham7793.github.io/.
And please excuse my horrendous CSS and HTML.
